# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: language-identification
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:language-identification/language-identification] In natural language processing, **language identification** or **language guessing** is the problem of determining which natural language a given content is in.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] Computational approaches to this problem view it as a special case of text categorization, solved with various statistical methods.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] A common non-statistical intuitive approach (though highly uncertain) is to look for common letter combinations, or distinctive diacritics or punctuation.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] There are several statistical approaches to language identification.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] An older statistical method by Grefenstette was based on the frequency of short n-grams, which are often function morphemes.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] For example, "ing" is more common in English than in French, while the sequence "que" is more common in French.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] Given a new page found on the Web, one counts the number of occurrences of each such short sequence and picks the language whose frequency table it matches the most.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] One technique is to compare the compressibility of the text to the compressibility of texts in a set of known languages.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] This approach is known as mutual information based distance measure.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] The same technique can also be used to empirically construct family trees of languages which closely correspond to the trees constructed using historical methods.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] Mutual information based distance measure is essentially equivalent to more conventional model-based methods and is not generally considered to be either novel or better than simpler techniques.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] Another technique, as described by Cavnar and Trenkle (1994) and Dunning (1994) is to create a language n-gram model from a "training text" for each of the languages.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] These models can be based on characters (Cavnar and Trenkle) or encoded bytes (Dunning); in the latter, language identification and character encoding detection are integrated.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] Then, for any piece of text needing to be identified, a similar model is made, and that model is compared to each stored language model.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] The most likely language is the one with the model that is most similar to the model from the text needing to be identified.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] This approach can be problematic when the input text is in a language for which there is no model.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] In that case, the method may return another, "most similar" language as its result.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] Also problematic for any approach are pieces of input text that are composed of several languages, as is common on the Web.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] As of 2025, a commonly used baseline method is via the fastText library, which has comparable classification accuracy as deep learning techniques, but much faster.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] One of the great bottlenecks of language identification systems is to distinguish between closely related languages.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] Similar languages like Bulgarian and Macedonian or Indonesian and Malay present significant lexical and structural overlap, making it challenging for systems to discriminate between them.
[src:language-identification/language-identification] The best system reached performance of over 95% results (Goutte et al., 2014).
[src:language-identification/language-identification] Results of the DSL shared task are described in Zampieri et al.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A rule-based program, performing lexical tokenization, is called *tokenizer*, or *scanner*, although *scanner* is also a term for the first stage of a lexer.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A lexer forms the first phase of a compiler frontend in processing.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Lexers and parsers are most often used for compilers, but can be used for other computer language tools, such as prettyprinters or linters.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Lexing can be divided into two stages: the *scanning*, which segments the input string into syntactic units called *lexemes* and categorizes these into token classes, and the *evaluating*, which converts lexemes into processed values.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Lexers are generally quite simple, with most of the complexity deferred to the syntactic analysis or semantic analysis phases, and can often be generated by a lexer generator, notably lex or derivatives.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] However, lexers can sometimes include some complexity, such as phrase structure processing to make input easier and simplify the parser, and may be written partly or fully by hand, either to support more features or for performance.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing is not equal to what is called lexeme in linguistics.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing can be equal to the linguistic equivalent only in analytic languages, such as English, but not in highly synthetic languages, such as fusional languages.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] What is called a lexeme in rule-based natural language processing is more similar to what is called a word in linguistics (not to be confused with a word in computer architecture), although in some cases it may be more similar to a morpheme.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A *lexical token* is a string with an assigned and thus identified meaning, in contrast to the probabilistic token used in large language models.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A lexical token consists of a *token name* and an optional *token value*.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The token name is a category of a rule-based lexical unit.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A token name is what might be termed a part of speech in linguistics.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] the string is not implicitly segmented on spaces, as a natural language speaker would do.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The raw input, the 43 characters, must be explicitly split into the 9 tokens with a given space delimiter (i.e., matching the string `" "` or regular expression `/\s{1}/`).
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] When a token class represents more than one possible lexeme, the lexer often saves enough information to reproduce the original lexeme, so that it can be used in semantic analysis.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The parser typically retrieves this information from the lexer and stores it in the abstract syntax tree.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] This is necessary in order to avoid information loss in the case where numbers may also be valid identifiers.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Tokens are identified based on the specific rules of the lexer.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Some methods used to identify tokens include regular expressions, specific sequences of characters termed a flag, specific separating characters called delimiters, and explicit definition by a dictionary.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Special characters, including punctuation characters, are commonly used by lexers to identify tokens because of their natural use in written and programming languages.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A lexical analyzer generally does nothing with combinations of tokens, a task left for a parser.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] For example, a typical lexical analyzer recognizes parentheses as tokens but does nothing to ensure that each "(" is matched with a ")".
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] When a lexer feeds tokens to the parser, the representation used is typically an enumerated type, which is a list of number representations.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] For example, "Identifier" can be represented with 0, "Assignment operator" with 1, "Addition operator" with 2, etc.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Tokens are often defined by regular expressions, which are understood by a lexical analyzer generator such as lex, or handcoded equivalent finite-state automata.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The lexical analyzer (generated automatically by a tool like lex or hand-crafted) reads in a stream of characters, identifies the lexemes in the stream, and categorizes them into tokens.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] If the lexer finds an invalid token, it will report an error.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] From there, the interpreted data may be loaded into data structures for general use, interpretation, or compiling.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The specification of a programming language often includes a set of rules, the lexical grammar, which defines the lexical syntax.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The lexical syntax is usually a regular language, with the grammar rules consisting of regular expressions; they define the set of possible character sequences (lexemes) of a token.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A lexer recognizes strings, and for each kind of string found, the lexical program takes an action, most simply producing a token.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Two important common lexical categories are white space and comments.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] These are also defined in the grammar and processed by the lexer but may be discarded (not producing any tokens) and considered *non-significant*, at most separating two tokens (as in `if x` instead of `ifx`).
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] There are two important exceptions to this.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] First, in off-side rule languages that delimit blocks with indenting, initial whitespace is significant, as it determines block structure, and is generally handled at the lexer level; see phrase structure, below.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Secondly, in some uses of lexers, comments and whitespace must be preserved – for examples, a prettyprinter also needs to output the comments and some debugging tools may provide messages to the programmer showing the original source code.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] In the 1960s, notably for ALGOL, whitespace and comments were eliminated as part of the line reconstruction phase (the initial phase of the compiler frontend), but this separate phase has been eliminated and these are now handled by the lexer.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The first stage, the *scanner*, is usually based on a finite-state machine (FSM).
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] It has encoded within it information on the possible sequences of characters that can be contained within any of the tokens it handles (individual instances of these character sequences are termed lexemes).
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] For example, an *integer* lexeme may contain any sequence of numerical digit characters.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] In some languages, the lexeme creation rules are more complex and may involve backtracking over previously read characters.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] For example, in C, one 'L' character is not enough to distinguish between an identifier that begins with 'L' and a wide-character string literal.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A lexeme, however, is only a string of characters known to be of a certain kind (e.g., a string literal, a sequence of letters).
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The second stage of a lexical analyzer, the *evaluator*, goes over the characters of the lexeme to produce a *value* containing relevant information for the parser.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The lexeme's type combined with its value is what properly constitutes a *token*.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The value in the token can be whatever is deemed necessary for the parser to interpret a token of that type.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The evaluator may also suppress a lexeme entirely, concealing it from the parser, which is useful for whitespace and comments.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] This is practical if the list of tokens is small, but lexers generated by automated tooling as part of a compiler-compiler toolchain are more practical for a larger number of potential tokens.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] These tools generally accept regular expressions that describe the tokens allowed in the input stream.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Each regular expression is associated with a production rule in the lexical grammar of the programming language that evaluates the lexemes matching the regular expression.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] These tools may generate source code that can be compiled and executed or construct a state transition table for a finite-state machine (which is plugged into template code for compiling and executing).
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Regular expressions compactly represent patterns that the characters in lexemes might follow.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] For example, for an English-based language, an IDENTIFIER token might be any English alphabetic character or an underscore, followed by any number of instances of ASCII alphanumeric characters and/or underscores.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] This could be represented compactly by the string `[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z_0-9]*`.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] This means "any character a-z, A-Z or _, followed by 0 or more of a-z, A-Z, _ or 0-9".
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] It takes a full parser to recognize such patterns in their full generality.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A parser can push parentheses on a stack and then try to pop them off and see if the stack is empty at the end (see example in the *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* book).
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Typically, lexical tokenization occurs at the word level.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] However, it is sometimes difficult to define what is meant by a "word".
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] In languages that use inter-word spaces (such as most that use the Latin alphabet, and most programming languages), this approach is fairly straightforward.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] However, even here there are many edge cases such as contractions, hyphenated words, emoticons, and larger constructs such as URIs (which for some purposes may count as single tokens).
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A classic example is "New York-based", which a naive tokenizer may break at the space even though the better break is (arguably) at the hyphen.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Tokenization is particularly difficult for languages written in scriptio continua, which exhibit no word boundaries, such as Ancient Greek, Chinese, or Thai.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Agglutinative languages, such as Korean, also make tokenization tasks complicated.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Some ways to address the more difficult problems include developing more complex heuristics, querying a table of common special cases, or fitting the tokens to a language model that identifies collocations in a later processing step.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Lexers are often generated by a *lexer generator*, analogous to parser generators, and such tools often come together.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The most established is lex, paired with the yacc parser generator, or rather some of their many reimplementations, like flex (often paired with GNU Bison).
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] These generators are a form of domain-specific language, taking in a lexical specification – generally regular expressions with some markup – and emitting a lexer.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] These tools yield very fast development, which is very important in early development, both to get a working lexer and because a language specification may change often.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Further, they often provide advanced features, such as pre- and post-conditions which are hard to program by hand.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] However, an automatically generated lexer may lack flexibility, and thus may require some manual modification, or an all-manually written lexer.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Lexer performance is a concern, and optimizing is worthwhile, more so in stable languages where the lexer runs very often (such as C or HTML). lex/flex-generated lexers are reasonably fast, but improvements of two to three times are possible using more tuned generators.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Hand-written lexers are sometimes used, but modern lexer generators produce faster lexers than most hand-coded ones.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The lex/flex family of generators uses a table-driven approach which is much less efficient than the directly coded approach.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] With the latter approach the generator produces an engine that directly jumps to follow-up states via goto statements.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Tools like re2c have proven to produce engines that are between two and three times faster than flex produced engines.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] It is in general difficult to hand-write analyzers that perform better than engines generated by these latter tools.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Lexical analysis mainly segments the input stream of characters into tokens, simply grouping the characters into pieces and categorizing them.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] However, the lexing may be significantly more complex; most simply, lexers may omit tokens or insert added tokens.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Omitting tokens, notably whitespace and comments, is very common when these are not needed by the compiler.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Less commonly, added tokens may be inserted.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] This is done mainly to group tokens into statements, or statements into blocks, to simplify the parser.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Line continuation is a feature of some languages where a newline is normally a statement terminator.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Most often, ending a line with a backslash (immediately followed by a newline) results in the line being *continued* – the following line is *joined* to the prior line.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] This is generally done in the lexer: The backslash and newline are discarded, rather than the newline being tokenized.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Examples include bash, other shell scripts and Python.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Many languages use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Most often this is mandatory, but in some languages the semicolon is optional in many contexts.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] This is mainly done at the lexer level, where the lexer outputs a semicolon into the token stream, despite one not being present in the input character stream, and is termed *semicolon insertion* or *automatic semicolon insertion*.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] In these cases, semicolons are part of the formal phrase grammar of the language, but may not be found in input text, as they can be inserted by the lexer.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Optional semicolons or other terminators or separators are also sometimes handled at the parser level, notably in the case of trailing commas or semicolons.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is a feature of BCPL and its distant descendant Go, though it is absent in B or C.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is present in JavaScript, though the rules are somewhat complex and much-criticized; to avoid bugs, some recommend always using semicolons, while others use initial semicolons, termed defensive semicolons, at the start of potentially ambiguous statements.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] The off-side rule (blocks determined by indenting) can be implemented in the lexer, as in Python, where increasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting an INDENT token and decreasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting one or more DEDENT tokens.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] These tokens correspond to the opening brace `{` and closing brace `}` in languages that use braces for blocks and means that the phrase grammar does not depend on whether braces or indenting are used.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] This requires that the lexer hold state, namely a stack of indent levels, and thus can detect changes in indenting when this changes, and thus the lexical grammar is not context-free: INDENT–DEDENT depend on the contextual information of prior indent levels.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Generally lexical grammars are context-free, or almost so, and thus require no looking back or ahead, or backtracking, which allows a simple, clean, and efficient implementation.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] This also allows simple one-way communication from lexer to parser, without needing any information flowing back to the lexer.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] These examples all only require lexical context, and while they complicate a lexer somewhat, they are invisible to the parser and later phases.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] A more complex example is the lexer hack in C, where the token class of a sequence of characters cannot be determined until the semantic analysis phase since typedef names and variable names are lexically identical but constitute different token classes.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] Thus in the hack, the lexer calls the semantic analyzer (say, symbol table) and checks if the sequence requires a typedef name.
[src:language-identification/lexical-analysis] In this case, information must flow back not from the parser only, but from the semantic analyzer back to the lexer, which complicates design.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] An ***n*-gram** is a sequence of *n* adjacent symbols in a particular order.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] The symbols may be *n* adjacent letters (including punctuation marks and blanks), syllables, or rarely whole words found in a language dataset; or adjacent phonemes extracted from a speech-recording dataset, or adjacent base pairs extracted from a genome.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] They are collected from a text corpus or speech corpus.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] If Latin numerical prefixes are used, then *n*-gram of size 1 is called a "unigram", size 2 a "bigram" (or, less commonly, a "digram") etc.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] If, instead of the Latin ones, the English cardinal numbers are furtherly used, then they are called "four-gram", "five-gram", etc.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] Similarly, Greek numerical prefixes such as "monomer", "dimer", "trimer", "tetramer", "pentamer", etc., or English cardinal numbers, "one-mer", "two-mer", "three-mer", etc. are used in computational biology for polymers or oligomers of a known size, called *k*-mers.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] When the items are words, n-grams may also be called *shingles*.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] In the context of natural language processing (NLP), the use of *n*-grams allows bag-of-words models to capture information such as word order, which would not be possible in the traditional bag of words setting.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] In 1951, Shannon discussed *n*-gram models of English.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] Figure 1 shows several example sequences and the corresponding 1-gram, 2-gram and 3-gram sequences.
[src:language-identification/n-gram] Here are further examples; these are word-level 3-grams and 4-grams (and counts of the number of times they appeared) from the Google *n*-gram corpus.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In statistics, **naive** (sometimes **simple** or **idiot's**) **Bayes classifiers** are a family of "probabilistic classifiers" which assume that the features are conditionally independent, given the target class.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In other words, a naive Bayes model assumes the information about the class provided by each variable is unrelated to the information from the others, with no information shared between the predictors.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The highly unrealistic nature of this assumption, called the **naive independence assumption**, is what gives the classifier its name.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] These classifiers are some of the simplest Bayesian network models.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes classifiers generally perform worse than more advanced models like logistic regressions, especially at quantifying uncertainty (with naive Bayes models often producing wildly overconfident probabilities).
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] However, they are highly scalable, requiring only one parameter for each feature or predictor in a learning problem.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Maximum-likelihood training can be done by evaluating a closed-form expression (simply by counting observations in each group), rather than the expensive iterative approximation algorithms required by most other models.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Despite the use of Bayes' theorem in the classifier's decision rule, naive Bayes is not (necessarily) a Bayesian method, and naive Bayes models can be fit to data using either Bayesian or frequentist methods.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes is a simple technique for constructing classifiers: models that assign class labels to problem instances, represented as vectors of feature values, where the class labels are drawn from some finite set.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] There is not a single algorithm for training such classifiers, but a family of algorithms based on a common principle: all naive Bayes classifiers assume that the value of a particular feature is independent of the value of any other feature, given the class variable.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, a fruit may be considered to be an apple if it is red, round, and about 10 cm in diameter.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] A naive Bayes classifier considers each of these features to contribute independently to the probability that this fruit is an apple, regardless of any possible correlations between the color, roundness, and diameter features.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In many practical applications, parameter estimation for naive Bayes models uses the method of maximum likelihood; in other words, one can work with the naive Bayes model without accepting Bayesian probability or using any Bayesian methods.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Despite their naive design and apparently oversimplified assumptions, naive Bayes classifiers have worked quite well in many complex real-world situations.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In 2004, an analysis of the Bayesian classification problem showed that there are sound theoretical reasons for the apparently implausible efficacy of naive Bayes classifiers.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Still, a comprehensive comparison with other classification algorithms in 2006 showed that Bayes classification is outperformed by other approaches, such as boosted trees or random forests.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] An advantage of naive Bayes is that it only requires a small amount of training data to estimate the parameters necessary for classification.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The problem with the above formulation is that if the number of features n is large or if a feature can take on a large number of values, then basing such a model on probability tables is infeasible.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The model must therefore be reformulated to make it more tractable.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In practice, there is interest only in the numerator of that fraction, because the denominator does not depend on C and the values of the features $x_{i}$ are given, so that the denominator is effectively constant.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Now the "naive" conditional independence assumptions come into play: assume that all features in $\mathbf {x}$ are mutually independent, conditional on the category $C_{k}$ .
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Often, it is only necessary to discriminate between classes.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] One is that it allows an interpretation in information theory, where log-probabilities are units of information in nats.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Another is that it avoids arithmetic underflow.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The discussion so far has derived the independent feature model, that is, the naive Bayes probability model.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The naive Bayes classifier combines this model with a decision rule.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] One common rule is to pick the hypothesis that is most probable so as to minimize the probability of misclassification; this is known as the *maximum *a posteriori** or *MAP* decision rule.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The assumptions on distributions of features are called the "event model" of the naive Bayes classifier.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] For discrete features like the ones encountered in document classification (include spam filtering), multinomial and Bernoulli distributions are popular.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] These assumptions lead to two distinct models, which are often confused.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] When dealing with continuous data, a typical assumption is that the continuous values associated with each class are distributed according to a normal (or Gaussian) distribution.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, suppose the training data contains a continuous attribute, **x**.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The data is first segmented by the class, and then the mean and variance of x is computed in each class.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Let $\mu _{k}$ be the mean of the values in x associated with class $C_{k}$ , and let $\sigma _{k}^{2}$ be the Bessel corrected variance of the values in x associated with class $C_{k}$ .
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Suppose one has collected some observation value v .
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Then, the probability *density* of v given a class $C_{k}$ , i.e., $p(x=v\mid C_{k})$ , can be computed by plugging v into the equation for a normal distribution parameterized by $\mu _{k}$ and $\sigma _{k}^{2}$ .
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Another common technique for handling continuous values is to use binning to discretize the feature values and obtain a new set of Bernoulli-distributed features.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Some literature suggests that this is required in order to use naive Bayes, but it is not true, as the discretization may throw away discriminative information.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Sometimes the distribution of class-conditional marginal densities is far from normal.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In these cases, kernel density estimation can be used for a more realistic estimate of the marginal densities of each class.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This method, which was introduced by John and Langley, can boost the accuracy of the classifier considerably.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] With a multinomial event model, samples (feature vectors) represent the frequencies with which certain events have been generated by a multinomial $(p_{1},\dots ,p_{n})$ where $p_{i}$ is the probability that event i occurs (or K such multinomials in the multiclass case).
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] A feature vector $\mathbf {x} =(x_{1},\dots ,x_{n})$ is then a histogram, with $x_{i}$ counting the number of times event i was observed in a particular instance.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This is the event model typically used for document classification, with events representing the occurrence of a word in a single document (see bag of words assumption).
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Estimating the parameters in log space is advantageous since multiplying a large number of small values can lead to significant rounding error.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Applying a log transform reduces the effect of this rounding error.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] If a given class and feature value never occur together in the training data, then the frequency-based probability estimate will be zero, because the probability estimate is directly proportional to the number of occurrences of a feature's value.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This is problematic because it will wipe out all information in the other probabilities when they are multiplied.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Therefore, it is often desirable to incorporate a small-sample correction, called pseudocount, in all probability estimates such that no probability is ever set to be exactly zero.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This way of regularizing naive Bayes is called Laplace smoothing when the pseudocount is one, and Lidstone smoothing in the general case.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In the multivariate Bernoulli event model, features are independent Boolean variables (binary variables) describing inputs.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Like the multinomial model, this model is popular for document classification tasks, where binary term occurrence features are used rather than term frequencies.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This event model is especially popular for classifying short texts.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] It has the benefit of explicitly modelling the absence of terms.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Note that a naive Bayes classifier with a Bernoulli event model is not the same as a multinomial NB classifier with frequency counts truncated to one.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Re-train the model based on the *probabilities* (not the labels) predicted in the previous step.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Convergence is determined based on improvement to the model likelihood $P(D\mid \theta )$ , where $\theta$ denotes the parameters of the naive Bayes model.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This training algorithm is an instance of the more general expectation–maximization algorithm (EM): the prediction step inside the loop is the *E*-step of EM, while the re-training of naive Bayes is the *M*-step.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The algorithm is formally justified by the assumption that the data are generated by a mixture model, and the components of this mixture model are exactly the classes of the classification problem.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Despite the fact that the far-reaching independence assumptions are often inaccurate, the naive Bayes classifier has several properties that make it surprisingly useful in practice.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In particular, the decoupling of the class conditional feature distributions means that each distribution can be independently estimated as a one-dimensional distribution.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This helps alleviate problems stemming from the curse of dimensionality, such as the need for data sets that scale exponentially with the number of features.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] While naive Bayes often fails to produce a good estimate for the correct class probabilities, this may not be a requirement for many applications.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, the naive Bayes classifier will make the correct MAP decision rule classification so long as the correct class is predicted as more probable than any other class.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This is true regardless of whether the probability estimate is slightly, or even grossly inaccurate.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In this manner, the overall classifier can be robust enough to ignore serious deficiencies in its underlying naive probability model.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Other reasons for the observed success of the naive Bayes classifier are discussed in the literature cited below.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This is exactly a logistic regression classifier.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The link between the two can be seen by observing that the decision function for naive Bayes (in the binary case) can be rewritten as "predict class $C_{1}$ if the odds of $p(C_{1}\mid \mathbf {x} )$ exceed those of $p(C_{2}\mid \mathbf {x} )$ ".
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The left-hand side of this equation is the log-odds, or *logit*, the quantity predicted by the linear model that underlies logistic regression.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Since naive Bayes is also a linear model for the two "discrete" event models, it can be reparametrised as a linear function $b+\mathbf {w} ^{\top }x>0$ .
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Obtaining the probabilities is then a matter of applying the logistic function to $b+\mathbf {w} ^{\top }x$ , or in the multiclass case, the softmax function.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Discriminative classifiers have lower asymptotic error than generative ones; however, research by Ng and Jordan has shown that in some practical cases naive Bayes can outperform logistic regression because it reaches its asymptotic error faster.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Problem: classify whether a given person is a male or a female based on the measured features.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The features include height, weight, and foot size.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Although with NB classifier we treat them as independent, they are not in reality.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The following example assumes equiprobable classes so that P(male)= P(female) = 0.5.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This prior probability distribution might be based on prior knowledge of frequencies in the larger population or in the training set.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Below is a sample to be classified as male or female.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In order to classify the sample, one has to determine which posterior is greater, male or female.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] However, given the sample, the evidence is a constant and thus scales both posteriors equally.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] It therefore does not affect classification and can be ignored.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Note that a value greater than 1 is OK here – it is a probability density rather than a probability, because *height* is a continuous variable.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Since posterior numerator is greater in the female case, the prediction is that the sample is female.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Here is a worked example of naive Bayesian classification to the document classification problem.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Consider the problem of classifying documents by their content, for example into spam and non-spam e-mails.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The question that has to be answered is: "what is the probability that a given document *D* belongs to a given class *C*?" In other words, what is $p(C\mid D)\,$ ?
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Thus, the probability ratio p(*S* | *D*) / p(¬*S* | *D*) can be expressed in terms of a series of likelihood ratios.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The actual probability p(*S* | *D*) can be easily computed from log (p(*S* | *D*) / p(¬*S* | *D*)) based on the observation that p(*S* | *D*) + p(¬*S* | *D*) = 1.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] (This technique of "log-likelihood ratios" is a common technique in statistics.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Finally, the document can be classified as follows.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] It is spam if $p(S\mid D)>p(\neg S\mid D)$ (i. e., $\ln {p(S\mid D) \over p(\neg S\mid D)}>0$ ), otherwise it is not spam.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes classifiers are a popular statistical technique of e-mail filtering.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] They typically use bag-of-words features to identify email spam, an approach commonly used in text classification.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Naive Bayes classifiers work by correlating the use of tokens (typically words, or sometimes other things), with spam and non-spam e-mails and then using Bayes' theorem to calculate a probability that an email is or is not spam.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Variants of the basic technique have been implemented in a number of research works and commercial software products.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Many modern mail clients implement Bayesian spam filtering.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Users can also install separate email filtering programs.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Server-side email filters, such as DSPAM, Rspamd, SpamAssassin, SpamBayes, Bogofilter, and ASSP, make use of Bayesian spam filtering techniques, and the functionality is sometimes embedded within mail server software itself.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] CRM114, often cited as a Bayesian filter, is not intended to use a Bayes filter in production, but includes the ″unigram″ feature for reference.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] In the case a word has never been met during the learning phase, both the numerator and the denominator are equal to zero, both in the general formula and in the spamicity formula.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The software can decide to discard such words for which there is no information available.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] More generally, the words that were encountered only a few times during the learning phase cause a problem, because it would be an error to trust blindly the information they provide.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] A simple solution is to simply avoid taking such unreliable words into account as well.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This corrected probability is used instead of the spamicity in the combining formula.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This formula can be extended to the case where *n* is equal to zero (and where the spamicity is not defined), and evaluates in this case to $Pr(S)$ .
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] "Neutral" words like "the", "a", "some", or "is" (in English), or their equivalents in other languages, can be ignored.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] More generally, some bayesian filtering filters simply ignore all the words which have a spamicity next to 0.5, as they contribute little to a good decision.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The words taken into consideration are those whose spamicity is next to 0.0 (distinctive signs of legitimate messages), or next to 1.0 (distinctive signs of spam).
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] A method can be for example to keep only those ten words, in the examined message, which have the greatest absolute value |0.5 − *pI*|.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Some software products take into account the fact that a given word appears several times in the examined message, others don't.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Some software products use *patterns* (sequences of words) instead of isolated natural languages words.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, with a "context window" of four words, they compute the spamicity of "Viagra is good for", instead of computing the spamicities of "Viagra", "is", "good", and "for".
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] This method gives more sensitivity to context and eliminates the Bayesian noise better, at the expense of a bigger database.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Depending on the implementation, Bayesian spam filtering may be susceptible to Bayesian poisoning, a technique used by spammers in an attempt to degrade the effectiveness of spam filters that rely on Bayesian filtering.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] A spammer practicing Bayesian poisoning will send out emails with large amounts of legitimate text (gathered from legitimate news or literary sources).
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Spammer tactics include insertion of random innocuous words that are not normally associated with spam, thereby decreasing the email's spam score, making it more likely to slip past a Bayesian spam filter.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] However, with (for example) Paul Graham's scheme only the most significant probabilities are used, so that padding the text out with non-spam-related words does not affect the detection probability significantly.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Words that normally appear in large quantities in spam may also be transformed by spammers.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] For example, «Viagra» would be replaced with «Viaagra» or «V!agra» in the spam message.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The recipient of the message can still read the changed words, but each of these words is met more rarely by the Bayesian filter, which hinders its learning process.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] As a general rule, this spamming technique does not work very well, because the derived words end up recognized by the filter just like the normal ones.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Another technique used to try to defeat Bayesian spam filters is to replace text with pictures, either directly included or linked.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The whole text of the message, or some part of it, is replaced with a picture where the same text is "drawn".
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] The spam filter is usually unable to analyze this picture, which would contain the sensitive words like «Viagra».
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] However, since many mail clients disable the display of linked pictures for security reasons, the spammer sending links to distant pictures might reach fewer targets.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Also, a picture's size in bytes is bigger than the equivalent text's size, so the spammer needs more bandwidth to send messages directly including pictures.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] Some filters are more inclined to decide that a message is spam if it has mostly graphical contents.
[src:language-identification/naive-bayes-classifier] A solution used by Google in its Gmail email system is to perform an OCR (Optical Character Recognition) on every mid to large size image, analyzing the text inside.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] When classification is performed by a computer, statistical methods are normally used to develop the algorithm.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Often, the individual observations are analyzed into a set of quantifiable properties, known variously as explanatory variables or *features*.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] These properties may variously be categorical (e.g.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"), integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email) or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Other classifiers work by comparing observations to previous observations by means of a similarity or distance function.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] An algorithm that implements classification, especially in a concrete implementation, is known as a **classifier**.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] The term "classifier" sometimes also refers to the mathematical function, implemented by a classification algorithm, that maps input data to a category.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Terminology across fields is quite varied.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] In machine learning, the observations are often known as *instances*, the explanatory variables are termed *features* (grouped into a feature vector), and the possible categories to be predicted are *classes*.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Other fields may use different terminology: e.g. in community ecology, the term "classification" normally refers to cluster analysis.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Classification and clustering are examples of the more general problem of pattern recognition, which is the assignment of some sort of output value to a given input value.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] A common subclass of classification is probabilistic classification.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Algorithms of this nature use statistical inference to find the best class for a given instance.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Unlike other algorithms, which simply output a "best" class, probabilistic algorithms output a probability of the instance being a member of each of the possible classes.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] The best class is normally then selected as the one with the highest probability.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Early work on statistical classification was undertaken by Fisher, in the context of two-group problems, leading to Fisher's linear discriminant function as the rule for assigning a group to a new observation.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] This early work assumed that data-values within each of the two groups had a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] The extension of this same context to more than two groups has also been considered with a restriction imposed that the classification rule should be linear.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Unlike frequentist procedures, Bayesian classification procedures provide a natural way of taking into account any available information about the relative sizes of the different groups within the overall population.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Bayesian procedures tend to be computationally expensive and, in the days before Markov chain Monte Carlo computations were developed, approximations for Bayesian clustering rules were devised.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Some Bayesian procedures involve the calculation of group-membership probabilities: these provide a more informative outcome than a simple attribution of a single group-label to each new observation.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Classification can be thought of as two separate problems – binary classification and multiclass classification.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] In binary classification, a better understood task, only two classes are involved, whereas multiclass classification involves assigning an object to one of several classes.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Since many classification methods have been developed specifically for binary classification, multiclass classification often requires the combined use of multiple binary classifiers.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Most algorithms describe an individual instance whose category is to be predicted using a feature vector of individual, measurable properties of the instance.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Each property is termed a feature, also known in statistics as an explanatory variable (or independent variable, although features may or may not be statistically independent).
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"); integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email); or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] If the instance is an image, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image; if the instance is a piece of text, the feature values might be occurrence frequencies of different words.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Some algorithms work only in terms of discrete data and require that real-valued or integer-valued data be *discretized* into groups (e.g. less than 5, between 5 and 10, or greater than 10).
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] A large number of algorithms for classification can be phrased in terms of a linear function that assigns a score to each possible category *k* by combining the feature vector of an instance with a vector of weights, using a dot product.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] The predicted category is the one with the highest score.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] In discrete choice theory, where instances represent people and categories represent choices, the score is considered the utility associated with person *i* choosing category *k*.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Algorithms with this basic setup are known as linear classifiers.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] What distinguishes them is the procedure for determining (training) the optimal weights/coefficients and the way that the score is interpreted.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Since no single form of classification is appropriate for all data sets, a large toolkit of classification algorithms has been developed.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] Choices between different possible algorithms are frequently made on the basis of quantitative evaluation of accuracy.
[src:language-identification/statistical-classification] In some of these, it is employed as a data mining procedure, while in others more detailed statistical modeling is undertaken.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] In linguistics and natural language processing, a **corpus** (pl.: **corpora**) or **text corpus** is a dataset, consisting of natively digital and older, digitalized, language resources, either annotated or unannotated.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] Annotated, they have been used in corpus linguistics for statistical hypothesis testing, checking occurrences or validating linguistic rules within a specific language territory.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] A corpus may contain texts in a single language (*monolingual corpus*) or text data in multiple languages (*multilingual corpus*).
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] In order to make the corpora more useful for doing linguistic research, they are often subjected to a process known as annotation.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] An example of annotating a corpus is part-of-speech tagging, or *POS-tagging*, in which information about each word's part of speech (verb, noun, adjective, etc.) is added to the corpus in the form of *tags*.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] Another example is indicating the lemma (base) form of each word.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] When the language of the corpus is not a working language of the researchers who use it, interlinear glossing is used to make the annotation bilingual.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] Some corpora have further *structured* levels of analysis applied.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] In particular, smaller corpora may be fully parsed.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] Such corpora are usually called Treebanks or Parsed Corpora.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] The difficulty of ensuring that the entire corpus is completely and consistently annotated means that these corpora are usually smaller, containing around one to three million words.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] Other levels of linguistic structured analysis are possible, including annotations for morphology, semantics and pragmatics.
[src:language-identification/text-corpus] Corpora are the main knowledge base in corpus linguistics.
